# Code Standards

The project uses **TypeScript**. Follow the **Google TypeScript Style Guide** and DRY, KISS, and SRP principles.

## Google Style Guide (summary)

- **Encoding**: UTF-8. **Indentation**: 2 spaces (no tabs).
- **File order**: imports → implementation; one blank line between sections.
- **Naming**: `UpperCamelCase` (classes, interfaces, types); `lowerCamelCase` (variables, functions, props); `CONSTANT_CASE` (constants, enum values).
- **Imports**: Prefer named imports; default import only when required by the library.
- No underscore prefixes or suffixes on identifiers.

## DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself)

- Extract repeated strings (e.g. i18n copy) into dedicated modules or files.
- Reusable components and functions instead of copying code.
- Centralize constants and theme values (colors, breakpoints).

## KISS (Keep It Simple, Stupid)

- Prefer straightforward solutions; avoid premature abstraction.
- Functions and components with a clear responsibility and self-explanatory names.

## SRP (Single Responsibility Principle)

- One function does one thing; one component represents one UI concept or logical block.
- Separate business logic from presentation (composables vs components).
- One CSS file per “responsibility” (variables, layout, components, utilities).

## Example

```typescript
// ❌ Avoid: function doing too much
function handleUser(data) {
  validate(data);
  saveToDb(data);
  sendEmail(data);
  updateCache(data);
}

// ✅ Prefer: one responsibility per function
function validateUserData(data) { /* ... */ }
function persistUser(data) { /* ... */ }
```
